03933nam a22006135i 9788366675094DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20202020pl     fo  d z      eng d  a97883666750947 a10.2478/97883666750942doi  a(DE-B1597)571722  a(OCoLC)1224279558  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aplcPL 7aART0570002bisacsh1 aDeaca, Mircea Valeriu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Control Cycle in Film :bCircular Coupling from Brain to Culture /cMircea Valeriu Deaca. 1aWarsaw ;aBerlin : bSciendo, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (726 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Cognitive Grammar Notions -- t2. A General Description of the Control Cycle -- t3. The Enactive Approach of Sense-making -- t4. The Grounded Approach of Perception and Action -- t5. The Attention Schema -- t6. The Predictive Brain -- t7. The Constructed Emotions -- t8. The Grounded Simulation: Verbal and Visual Couplings -- t9. The Descriptive System -- t10. The E-site -- t11. The Image Pole and Object Pole -- t12. The Reference Point and Metonymy -- t13. The Metaphor -- t14. Circular Couplings in Cinematographic Constructions -- t15. The Motion -- t16. The Narrative Roles -- t17. The Conceptual Domains of Film Analysis -- tReferences -- tFilm index -- tTerms index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe aim of the present study is theoretical. The question set up for examination is whether there is a cognitive model that underpins human sense-making in the context of film experience. The conceptual resources provided by Cognitive grammar (as elaborated by Ronald W. Langacker), the recent developments of the neuroscience of emotions (as advocated by Lawrence Barsalou, Lisa Feldman Barrett, and Giovanna Colombetti), the theory of attention advocated by Michael S. A. Graziano, and several suggestions from the embodied-enactive approach (in the works of Evan Thompson and Maxine Johnson-Smith) seemed particularly useful coordinates for this research composed of analytical reflections. The study focuses on the cognitive model based on the action of control, understood as an explanatory instrument for creating meaning, and follows up with the possible applications in the domain of film analysis. The work is the result of collaborative research spurred by theoretical advances and hypotheses from neuroscience, neurolinguistics, and film theory and analysis. On the account developed here, the structure of the control cycle cognitive model is regarded as central to sense-making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh0 cprintz978836667510040uhttps://sciendo.com/book/9788366675094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9788366675094/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK